---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";

const title = "Cmd+kit | Playground Docs";
const description =
  "Learn how to use the Cmd+kit playground to configure commands, preview behavior, and export production-ready starter code.";
---

<DocsLayout description={description} locale="en" title={title}>
      <p class="eyebrow">Playground</p>
      <h1>Playground Guide</h1>
      <p>
        The playground is the fastest way to shape a `Cmd+kit` integration before moving the
        result into your codebase. It lets you configure the command model, test the interaction
        flow in a live preview, and export starter code for the supported adapters.
      </p>

      <h2>What the playground is for</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>prototype your command palette structure without editing source files first</li>
        <li>test nested navigation, search behavior, and command grouping in real time</li>
        <li>adjust theme tokens and copy before integrating the package</li>
        <li>export starter snippets for React, Vue, Preact, vanilla browser code, CSS, Tailwind, and JSON</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Main areas</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Basics</strong>: title, keyboard shortcut, source mode, and high-level settings</li>
        <li><strong>Sections</strong>: create groups of commands and edit each item</li>
        <li><strong>Nested commands</strong>: add child sections to model drill-down navigation</li>
        <li><strong>Messages</strong>: customize placeholder, empty state, and related UI copy</li>
        <li><strong>Theme</strong>: tune accent, surface, border, text, radius, and shadow values</li>
        <li><strong>Preview</strong>: validate the interaction and keyboard flow live</li>
        <li><strong>Code</strong>: export the current config in the format you need</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How to work with it</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Start by defining your root sections and the commands inside each one.</li>
        <li>Add shortcuts, links, subtitles, and keywords where they improve discoverability.</li>
        <li>Create nested sections for flows that should drill into a second level.</li>
        <li>Adjust messages and theme tokens until the preview matches your product.</li>
        <li>Switch the export target and copy the generated starter code into your app.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Source modes</h2>
      <p>
        The playground supports both static and async-style configuration. Use static mode to model
        inline sections. Use async mode when your final integration will load commands from an API
        or another runtime source and you want to verify loading behavior earlier.
      </p>

      <h2>Exports</h2>
      <p>
        The generated code is meant to be a practical starting point, not a locked template. You
        should treat the export as the base integration and then continue refining naming, styles,
        and application-specific behavior inside your own codebase.
      </p>

      <h2>Best practice</h2>
      <p>
        Use the playground to converge on structure and configuration quickly, then move to the
        package documentation pages for the production API details. The playground is the fastest
        design and onboarding tool; the docs remain the source of truth for integration patterns.
      </p>
</DocsLayout>
